<section class="faq" aria-labelledby="faq-heading">
  <div class="section-head">
    <span class="section-eyebrow" id="faq-heading">&#9670; COMMON QUESTIONS</span>
    <span class="section-rule"></span>
  </div>
  <div class="faq-list">
    <div class="faq-item">
      <h2 class="faq-q">Does Shopify have a gift message option at checkout?</h2>
      <p class="faq-a">Not as a real, dedicated field on a standard store. The only native place for a shopper to leave a note is the cart order-note box, which is a single freeform field for the whole order, unlabeled unless you rename it, and off by default in many themes. It was built for delivery instructions, not gifting, so a gift message shares one field with everything else, does not attach to a specific item, and has no validation. Gift wrap at checkout is native only for Shopify Plus stores using Checkout Extensibility, and even there it is a bare option rather than a fee, a line item, and a packing instruction. Everyone else stitches gifting together with the order note, theme edits, and apps.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <h2 class="faq-q">Why doesn't my Shopify gift note show on the packing slip?</h2>
      <p class="faq-a">Because the packing slip is one template for every order, and the order note does not print on it unless you edit the Liquid template to pull the note in. Even after you do, the note prints on every order that has one, gift or not, and it prints alongside the full prices, because there is no native switch to hide prices for a gift. So the recipient can open a box that shows what the sender paid, which is the opposite of a gift. Getting the message onto the slip and the prices off it, for gift orders only, is theme code plus a manual habit, and it breaks the first time an order is edited or a warehouse app takes over fulfillment.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <h2 class="faq-q">How do I hide prices on a Shopify gift receipt?</h2>
      <p class="faq-a">There is no native per-order toggle that says this order is a gift, hide the prices. The packing slip template is shared across the whole store, so hiding prices there hides them for every order, and leaving them shows them on gifts too. The dependable way is to mark an order as a gift the moment it is placed, then generate a separate gift packing slip for those orders that carries the message and omits every price and total, while normal orders keep their standard slip. That means detecting the gift, tagging the order, and branching the document, which is exactly the judgement a shared template cannot make on its own.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

